Title: Los Angeles Times Photographs Collection
Description.abstract: Collection consists of photonegatives documenting events and people in So. CA and photographic prints documenting events and people in So. CA, the US, and the world. The material originates from the Los Angeles Times newspaper and includes glass negatives (ca. 1918-1932), nitrate negatives (ca. 1925-45), and safety negatives (ca. 1935-1990). Also includes prints and negatives from the Los Angeles Times Orange County and San Diego bureaus.

Title: Know Your City No.1 Spring Street entrance to Los Angeles City hall
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.1--This is easy.  Great ones have passed here.  So have a lot of briefcases.  And resolutions. To and fro people go and seldom see what camera does.  No contest, no prizes.  Just fun, what is it? Answer, Page 30, Part II.
Description.note: ANSWER: Sure, it's the Spring St. entrance to the City hall, the picture being taken from north to south to show the row of pillars from a seldom-seen angle. And how many of the thousands of persons who pass here daily have bothered to notice the fancy colorful tilework over this pillared portal?

Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.3 View down alleyway at Angels Flight car  Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.3 -- It is here that Angels do not have feet of clay.  They ride. It's a neighborhood of ups and downs.  And a nickel gets you a lot of pull.  This is an unusual angle of -- can you guess, just for fun?  The answer on Page 2, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER:The photo shows Angels Flight as it crosses over Clay St. ("It is here angels do not have feet of clay" -- wow!) And a nickel does give you a lot of pull here because the cost of a round-trip ticket on this, the city's smallest franchised railroad, is -- 5 cents. But you probably guessed it. That angular car was a dead giveaway

Title: Know Your City No.4 Beethoven statue in Pershing Square, Los Angeles, 1955
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.4 -- For years he was for the birds.  But he went away for a while.  And when he came back he was looking the other way.  And, if he could, he'd probably make a note of that.  Just for fun, who is he? And where is he?  Answer on Page 9, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Surely you recognized the statue, in studied stride, of Beethoven that stands in Pershing Square. The statue faces the intersection of 5th and Olive Sts., being out in this new position after having been stored during the excavation for the parking garage beneath the park

Title: Know Your City No.7 Mary Andrews Clark Memorial House
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.7 -- A man's home may be his castle.  But no men in this castle.  Just for a stopper, this place of stone was built with copper.  Strangely enough, those who live here worry about pay checks.  Answer on Page 34, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The impressive structure in the photo is the Mary Andrews Clark Memorial, a residence for working girls at 306 Loma Drive, at the corner of W 3rd St. Remember? It was built as a "living memorial" to his mother by Sen. Clark, the Montana "copper king."|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #158 by the City of Los Angeles in 1976.

Title: Know Your City No.8 Entrance to Hompa Hongwanja Buddhist Temple, Little Tokyo (Los Angeles), 1955
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 8--This is very familiar to its 2300 members. And to thousands more. Even gives you the address: 119 N Central Ave.,near corner of E 1st St.  Just for fun of it, can you guess what it is?  Find answer on Page 28, Part II.
Description.note: ANSWER:As you might suspect from its Oriental architecture, the building in the picture is the Hompa Hongwanja Buddhist Temple, a religious center in the heart of the city's Little Tokyo. It has been around a long time, since 1927. This is run strictly for your amusement|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #313 by the City of Los Angeles in 1986.

Title: Know Your City No.10 Los Angeles' Health Department Building on E 1st Street
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 10--It's a shame such a handsome building has to harbor as much ill feeling.  So modern!  And what a target for a kid with a sling-shot!  It's really easy.  But, just for fun, what and where is it?  The answer will be found on Page 3, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER:Right away, of course, you knew the structure in the photo is the new Health Department Building on E 1st St., between Main and Los Angeles Sts. This is the north side of it--as seen by the controversial statue in front of the new Police Building.

Title: Know Your City No.11 Obelisk at entrance to Griffith Observatory and Planetarium, Los Angeles, 1955
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.11--You can see more stars here than at any Hollywood premiere because it's one of the best night spots in town.  No liquor served, but you get that high feeling.  Just for fun, can you guess what it is?  Answer on Page 8, Part 2.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.12 -- Don't let that palm tree give you the wrong slant.  You know this place, even though it's name was changed a while ago.  In its day it has taken quite a paddling.  Can you guess where this picture was made?  Answer on Page 7, Part lll.
Description.note: ANSWER:Yes, Its MacArthur Park--formerly Westlake Park. In the photo, the view is northeasterly, across the lake, looking toward the boathouse and, behind that, the intersection of Alvarado St. and Wilshire Blvd.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 13 -- Some pretty important talk goes on behind doors facing this glistening corridor.  And the farther you go, the more important the doors.  That bronze plaque set in the floor is big, broad hint.  Look for the answer on Page 9, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER-- This is too easy. It is south corridor on Spring St. floor of the City Hall. At the end, to the left, the Mayor's office; to the right, offices of City Councilmen. Photo was made from City Hall's rotunda

Title: Know Your City No.15 Lionesses on archway of entrance to the Selig Zoo Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 15 -- This may be a toughie.  Because these are pretty lionesses.  They've been here since 1910. And never bitten anyone. Rather remotely, the last letter of the alphabet is involved.  Answer on Page 32, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The photo is of one of the ornate arches that formed the entrances to the old Selig Zoo, adjacent to Lincoln Park. Here, many early-day movies were made. Then, it was a regular zoo. And, at present, an inactive amusement park. But, nevertheless, down through the years and despite fallen plaster, it remains one of the most impressive entrances in town

Title: Know Your City No.17 Exterior view of the Mormon Temple on Santa Monica Blvd. in West Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 17 -- This is the largest of its kind in the world.  And its builders have some farther west than they originally intended.  Brand new, this structure is not yet wholly finished.  Figure on top is Angel Moroni.  Answer on Page 22, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: Captured from ground level in the photograph is the magnificent new Mormon Temple on Santa Monica Blvd. in West Los Angeles. Occupying an entire block, the temple and its grounds cost approximately $6,000,000 and constitute the religion's largest shrine, including the famous temple in Salt Lake City, Utah. It is incomplete only in that certain interior details are unfinished.

Title: Know Your City No.18 Muse of Music, Dance, Drama statuary at entrance to the Hollywood Bowl, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 18 -- This is a familiar symbol to people who go bowling.  But don't look for any tenpins, because it was built when a lot of people were in the alleys.  It still refuses to dance the music.  Just for fun, What?  Answer will be found on Page 32, Part2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Sure, it's the artistically modern statuary that overlooks the entrance to Hollywood Bowl. You've seen it hundreds of times. Its construction in 1940 was one of the last acts of the depression-- a WPA art project|~|The statuary entitled "Muse of Music, Dance, Drama" was designed by sculptor George Stanley

Name.subject: Mulholland, William, 1855-1935--Monuments
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.19; William Mulholland Memorial Fountain in Los Angeles, Calif., 1955
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 19 -- Always spouting off, that's this thing.  No fountain of youth, it's very colorful.  It's on a four-acre site where the man to whom it is dedicated lived as a boy.  Bet you didn't know that!  Can you guess it?  Answer on Page 31, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Naturally, its the city's most colorful fountain, the memorial to William Mulholland, "father" of Los Angeles' water supply. Located at Riverside Drive and Los Feliz Blvd., the fountain's changing sprays are dramatically illuminated with varying colored lights. It was dedicated on 1940. And, yes as a boy, Mulholland lived in a ramshackle farm on this very spot.

Title: Know Your City No.22 Night time view of Los Angeles' old Hall of Records
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 22 -- There isn't a manicurist in the place. But there's lots of filing.  And you might think there's be music.  But there is none.  Lots of important people in here.  Including Cupid.  If you can't guess, answer in on Page 32, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER:You surely recognized this as a night shot of the Hall of Records, made from the Spring St. side. Get the clues? -- "filing", Cupid (because the Marriage License Bureau is there)? And music? (Music-- Hall of Records, get it?)

Subject: Temples, Hindu--California--Los Angeles County|~|Landmarks
Name.subject: Vedanta Society of Southern California
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.23 Vedanta Temple at 1926 Vedanta Place Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 23 -- Here is peace.  And it was obscure -- until the freeway passed its door.  No movie set, it has the permanency of the ages--while the motorized world rushes past.  Just for fun, what and where is it?  The answer's on Page 24 of Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: This is the delightfully unique Church of the Vedanta, the world's oldest philosophical and religious order. Located in its own little square at 1926 Vedanta Place and surrounded by dormitories for students of the Vedas, it is on a hill that overlooked Hollywood -- until the freeway zoomed practically past its front steps. Built in 1938, it was unseen by many until the freeway passed. And many of those who speed by did not know about this unique temple-- until now.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 24 -- There are four of these.  And appropriately, the border of figures in relief depicts the various industries located in the area.  What and where is it?  Answer on Page 32, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: Pictured is one of the four ornamental posts on the Washington Blvd. bridge that crosses the Los Angeles River. The bridge is in the heart of the industrial district and lots of people probably go truckin' on by every day without noticing the interesting border of figures on the bridge's four main posts

Title: Know Your City No.26 Plaza Methodist Church at Olvera Street, Los Angeles, 1955
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 26 -- This tiled tower is on Sunset Blvd. And right beside is one of the city's greatest tourist attractions. This is kind of a tough on.  So give yourself an "A" if you can guess what it is.  Answer is on Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Sure it's on Sunset Blvd. -- EAST Sunset Blvd., right across from the Old Plaza. It is La Plaza Iglesia Metodista (the Plaza Methodist Church). Next door: Olvera Street.

Title: Know Your City No.29 Bridge and lake at Hollenbeck Park, Boyle Heights (Los Angeles), 1955
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 29 -- Look at that bridge again and you're almost certain to guess where this was taken.  Only one place in town with a span like that.  Its for people, not trains.  See Page 32, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Sure, it's the lake in Hollenbeck Park , the photo being made near the Boyle Ave. entrance. The park acquired its name for the very logical reason that most of its acreage was given to the city by Mrs. J.E. Hollenbeck. (Correction: It was erroneously reported that most of the acreage for the park was donated by Mrs. J.E.Hollenbeck. Actually, two-thirds of the property was donated by Mr. and Mrs. William H. Workman and it was their suggestion that the park be named for J.E. Hollenbeck, a close friend.) correction from 12/31/1955 paper

Description.note: ANSWER: In the foreground of the photo is the patio of the Casa de Adobe at 4603 N Figueroa St., an authentic replica of one of the city's first homes and which is part of the Southwest Museum, the building on the hill behind it.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #493 by the City of Los Angeles in 1990.

Title: Know Your City No.31 Tower of the Daughters of Charity of St. Vincent de Paul Los Angeles Orphanage at 917 S. Boyle Ave
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.31 -- For more than 60 years, there was girlish laughter around this stately structure.  But , now, only the pigeons live here.  Even though it is one of the city's prominent landmarks, can you guess what?  You'll find answer on Page 18, Part 1-A.
Description.note: ANSWER: Framed in stately palms by the camera is the tower of the old and abandoned Los Angeles Orphanage at 917 S Boyle Ave. Operated by the Daughters of Charity of St. Vincent de Paul, this home for girls was opened in 1890 and in use until 1953 when it was finally closed and a new home, called Maryvale, was opened in South San Gabriel.

Description.note: ANSWER: Heart-shaped? Sure, isn't this the heart of the city? It's the mosaic floor of the City Hall rotunda. And you knew it all the time, didnt you.?

Description.note: ANSWER: It is the miniature statue of St. Vincent de Paul and the children that stands on the lawn in front of St. Vincent's Hospital on W 3rd St., at Alvarado St.

Description.note: ANSWER: Of course -- building in the photo is Patriotic Hall at 1816 S Figueroa St., headquarters and meeting place of various service organizations.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 41 -- This sculpture is above the entrance of a well known building.  If you can recognize the two animals in bas-relief you're almost certain to get it.  You can find the answer to this question by turning to Page 20, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The two animals, distinguishable on either side of the throne, are the bull and the bear. Add that to the human figures holding the ticker tape and you could get only one answer: The Los Angeles Stock Exchange at 618 S Spring St.

Title: Know Your City No.43 Statue of Senator Stephen M. White at Los Angeles Civic Center
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.43 -- Surely you recognize this gentleman.  He's been standing there since 1907.  It's not everybody who can get a city into deep water and have a monument erected in his memory. If you cant figure it out, the answer is on Page 5, Part lll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The figure in the statue, which stands on the north lawn of the Hall of Records in the Civic Center, is that of Sen. Stephen M. White (1853-1901), who is known as the Father of Los Angeles Harbor inasmuch as he procured a Federal appropriation for construction of a deep-water harbor at San Pedro. The monument was erected by a grateful citizenry in 1907

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 45 -- Shown in this picture is a place that is really two things in one and, furthermore, it used to be something else.  And, it that has you completely confused, maybe the hedge will help.  You can become enlightened on Page 3, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: It is the Administration Building on the combined campus of Los Angeles City College and Los Angeles State College at 855 N Vermont Ave. Originally it was the site of the University of California, Southern Branch -- which moved to Westwood and is now UCLA

Title: Know Your City No.49. "Man and the Machine" sculpture and faade of the east door at Los Angeles County Museum
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY NO. 49 -- This ungracefully crouched fellow holding a wheel of industry is in front of an important door of an important building in prominent park.  He never has to go to the Rose Parade.  You'll find answer on Page 32, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This piece of unusual sculpture crouches in front of the old east door of the County Museum and he overlooks the rose garden of Exposition Park.|~|Cast stone sculpture by Donal Hord was funded by the Public Works of Art Project (PWAP) in 1934. The sculpture depicts a man crouching behind a wheel filled with gears and is variously known as "Man and the Wheel" or "Wheel of Industry" or "Man and the Machine." It was Hord's first PWAP project, and may have been the first many WPA sculpture projects created in Southern California.|~|Sculpture depicts a barefoot, muscular young man in working clothes in a squatting position. He is holding up a large wheel that rests on the ground in front of him. The interior of the wheel is cast in relief, with wheels, gears, and other symbols of the industrial age.

Title: Know Your City No.54 The Rochester, a Victorian apartment house at 1012 W Temple St. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 54 -- This ornate old house (now painted light green) is seen by tens of thousands every day.  Unfortunately, its origin and history are obscured by many owners and alterations.  Just a landmark.  Answer, Page 21, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Anyone who has ever traveled the freeways surely has noticed the old mansion, now converted into a rooming house. Its address is 1012 W Temple St., but it can be readily seen from the four-level structure of the freeways. If is just off southernbound lanes of the Harbor Freeway and it curves off the Hollywood Freeway. Recognize it now, don't' you?|~|The Rochester" was declared a historical-cultural monument by the city of Los Angeles on January 4, 1963 but was demolished in 1979.

Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.56; Exterior view of the Pico House and surrounding buildings, Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 56 -- Question is : Not where, but what is it?  (Buildings in background give away location.)  Anyway, it's historic and no series would be complete without it.  If you don't know, you'll never guess.  Answer on Page 6, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Si, Senor, it is the old Pico House, the oldest hotel in Los Angeles and little pueblo's first three-story structure. Built in 1869, it was the sensation of its day -- had floors and bathtubs. It was named, of course, after Pio Pico, last Mexican Governor of California. Its location is now designated as the southeast corner of Plaza and N Main Sts. That big square shape at the extreme right in the photograph is, of course, the Federal Building, and , beyond it, the tower of the City Hall.

Description.note: ANSWER: High number? Horns? Sure, what else could it be but Los Angeles Elks Lodge 99, located at 607 Park View St., across from MacArthur Park. Now, don't you feel rather foolish for not recognizing it?

Title: Know Your City No.68 Close up of a pylon-tower on 6th Street Viaduct over the Los Angeles River, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 68 -- I you guessed Sunday's picture (No. 66) in this series, this one shouldn't give you trouble.  This is no monument, regardless of how the camera sees it.  Answers is on Page 26, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: While Sunday's picture in this series was of the looping steel girders of the 6th St. viaduct over the Los Angeles River, today's is of one of the pylon-like concrete towers on the east end of the bridge. And about the only thing that can be said of them is that no other bridge in town has anything like 'em.

Description.note: ANSWER: If you didnt recognize the photo, surely the caption should have tipped you that the building is the National Guard Armory in Exposition Park. Simple,eh?

Title: Know Your City No.74 Statue of Don Felipe de Neve in the Old Plaza Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.74 -- this is a pretty famous fellow.  (Naturally -- otherwise, would they erect his statue?)  All you have to figure out is who he is, plus where this statue stands.  Cinch if you know Los Angeles history.  Answer Page 17, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: It is the statue of Don Felipe de Neve, generally recognized as the founder of El Pueblo Nuestra Senora la Reina de Los Angeles. The statue, erected by Parlor 247 of the Native Daughters of the Golden West, stands in the Old Plaza.

Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.77 Senator Frank Putnam Flint Memorial on grounds of Los Angeles City Hall
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.77 -- This is getting too easy.  Even if you didnt know, you can read the man's name on this memorial fountain.  Added hint:  There's a community named after him.  That leaves only the problem: Where is this?  Answers on Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Sure, it's the memorial to the late U.S. Sen. Frank Putnam Flint on the south, or 1st St., lawn of the City Hall. It was erected and dedicated in 1933. A prominent Southland attorney and developer before his death in 1929, Flint also was the founder of Flintridge Estate.

Title: Know Your City No.78 Memorial fountain and courtyard of Campo de Cahuenga, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.78 -- Although it shouldn't, this one may stump you.  You get no hints--other than this probably is one of most historically significant spots in California.  Something to do with signatures.  Answers on Page 31, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the picture is the memorial, Campo de Cahuenga, scene of the signing of the Treaty of Cahuenga by Lt. Col. John C. Fremont of the U.S. Army and Gen Andres Pico of the Mexican forces. By this treaty, signed Jan. 13, 1847, the United States acquired California. This memorial building and courtyard are at 3919 Lankershim Blvd., near the Los Angeles River and across the street from Universal City.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #29 by the City of Los Angeles in 1964.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.79 -- You can do a series like this just so long and then you work yourself into a hole--or a series of them.  Surely you can see through this picture.  In more ways than one.  Just for laughs where is it?  Page 8, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Sure, sure, sure-- all it is is a photo of the Figueroa St. tunnels on the Pasadena Freeway.  Sorry to be such a bore

Title: Know Your City No.80 Lake Hollywood and reservoir in 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 80 -- A beauty spot, this isolated lake is known to few.  It is only seconds from the city's most heavily traveled thoroughfare.  If it weren't for the haze, buildings could be seen in the background.  Answer, Page 16, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yes, this is lovely Lake Hollywood, a jewel in the hills just over the ridge from Cahuenga Pass.  Admission: Even the photographer didnt know it was there!  On a clear day, the taller buildings of Hollywood's business district are visible over the rim of the dam in the background.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #421 by the City of Los Angeles in 1989.

Title: Know Your City No.82 Abandoned oil well in Elysian Park hills with Los Angeles Civic Center in background
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.82 -- Naturally, you can guess what this is.  But, where you get around to where it is, you run into some interesting stuff.  (That City Hall tower ruins more mysteries!) Only recourse is to turn to the answer on Page 33, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Well, it's one of those old oil wells that are on the southern slopes of the Elysian Park hills, virtually a stone's throw from the bustling Civic Center.  This one is in the back yard of what was once the residence of Thomas O'Brien, once one of the finest "country homes outside Los Angeles."  Disonicio Sanchez has lived there for 30 years and, being pretty hep on the place's history, he should know.  Exact location is a knoll at the corner of W College and Centennial Sts.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.83 -- What that crazy guy is doing up there is beyond comprehension.  Because, of all the stairways in town, this is really the No.1 "Stairway to Nowhere."  Tens of thousands pass it every day. Guess what? Answer is on Page 38, Part l.

Title: Know Your City No.84 San Pedro Chamber of Commerce building with Port of Los Angeles in background
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.84 -- There shouldn't be much doubt as to WHERE this is, thus leaving you only the problem of WHAT it is.  It has quite a history, dating back to about 1906.  Maybe that dome will help.  Answer, Page 13, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Building in the photo--with the main channel of Los Angeles Harbor in the background--is the San Pedro Chamber of Commerce at 820 S Beacon St., San Pedro.  Building was originally a Carnegie library and, once upon a time, served as San Pedro's temporary City Hall.  Photo was made from roof of U.S. Post Office and Customs House.

Title: Know Your City No.87 The Islander ferry, that shuttles back and forth between San Pedro and Terminal Island, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.87 -- Here's something that's really in a rut.  Of course you can guess what it is because in all the city, this is the only one of its kind.  Whoever invented phrase, "to and fro" had this in mind.  Answer Page 8, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the Islander, the municipal ferry that shuttles back and forth between San Pedro and Terminal Island across the main channel of Los Angeles Harbor.

Title: Know Your City No.90 Entrance of the Pan-Pacific Auditorium, Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.90 -- From skates to baskets, this place has been on the pan for years.  It also has had boats, homes, automobiles, etc. Thousands upon thousands of people have been here.  Recognize it?  Answer on Page 9, Part lll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the entrance to the Pan-Pacific Auditorium out on Beverly Blvd., near Fairfax Ave., scene of numerous ice shows, basketball games and just about every other kind of exhibit.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #183 by the City of Los Angeles in 1978; it was destroyed by fire in 1989.

Title: Know Your City No.94 View of stairs and Royce Hall on the UCLA campus
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.94 -- Named after a philosopher, this imposing structure is one of the original buildings of a rapidly expanding institution.  There were a lot of sad people around here last Jan. 2.  Surely you know.  See Page 14, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: For the few who didn't recognize it, the structure in the picture is Royce Hall on the UCLA campus in Westwood.  Named after Philosopher Josiah Royce, the building houses liberal arts classrooms and a 3000-seat auditorium, largest on the campus.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.95 -- Funny thing about this place -- its most imposing views is from the back.  Which this is, as seen from a very busy street.  They may be a bunch of cutups, but there are a lot of big operators here.  Answer is on Page 32, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Of course, it's the back of the Hospital of the Good Samaritan, as seen from Wilshire Blvd.  And in their surgery they DO have a lot of big operators..

Title: Know Your City No.96 Entrance to the Pilgrimage Play [Ford] Amphitheater Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.96  -- Down through the years, thousands of persons, natives and tourists alike, have been here.  But chances are good that few of them will recognize it. Not in this light, anyway.  See answer on Page 10, Part lll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the picture and framed by the trees that surround it is the entrance to the Pilgrimage Play amphitheater in a little canyon in Cahuenga Pass, just across the Hollywood Freeway from the Hollywood Bowl.|~|Pilgrimage Play Amphitheater was built specifically for Christine Wetherill Stevenson's Pilgrimage Play. The original theater burned down in 1929 and this concrete design was built in 1931.  The theater was renamed John Anson Ford Amphitheatre in 1978 in honor of the Los Angeles County Supervisor who served from 1934-1958.

Title: Know Your City No.98 Side view of corner of Hollyhock House, residence of Aline Barnsdall, Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.98 -- A lot of people are going to go crazy trying to figure out this one.  Particularly with familiar landmark at lower left.  Best hint: Designed by famed architect, it used to be private, now is public.  See Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is a corner of the fabulous Barnsdall residence, designed by Architect Frank Lloyd Wright, which sits atop the knoll near the corner of Hollywood Blvd. and Vermont Ave.  The knoll was given to the city for a park, the residence becoming a city art gallery.  That landmark in the lower left corner of the photo is, of course, the Griffith Planetarium.|~|Hollyhock was built in 1919-1921 for oil heiress, Aline Barnsdall. In 1927 Barnsdall donated the house and acreage to the city of Los Angeles thus creating the Barnsdall Art Park.  Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #12 by the City of Los Angeles in 1963.

Name.subject: Barlow Medical Library (Los Angeles)
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.99 Entrance of the Barlow Medical Library Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.99 --  Here's one that's really a toughie.  Even if you can read the inscription on the building, there are few who will know exactly what or where it is.  Nevertheless, it has a definite niche in Los Angeles history.  See Page 26, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The Barlow Medical Library was built and stocked by the late Dr. Jarvis Barlow and might well be considered the origin of the Los Angeles County Medical Association.  Situated at 742 N Broadway, it is across the street from a day health clinic operated as sort of an extension by the University of California.  Both are now abandoned, the library finally closing during World War II, the clinic being shuttered in 1952.  Out of the Barlow Medical Foundation grew the present Los Angeles County Medical Association.|~|The Barlow Medical Library collection was transferred to UCLA in 1992 when the Los Angeles County Medical Association closed it's library.

Title: Know Your City No.100 Side view of tower and street of Hollywood United Methodist Church Hollywood, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.100 -- Yep, up to 100 already.  To observe occasion properly, we should've pictured something on Century Blvd. But we didn't.  What you see here is in just the opposite direction.  You've seen it lots of times.  See Page 5, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: If you missed this one, you ought to be ashamed of yourself.  Because it is one of the most familiar church towers in town.  Right at a very busy corner, too.  Sure, it's the First Methodist Church at Highland and Franklin Aves., in Hollywood.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #248 by the City of Los Angeles in 1981.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.102 -- This is the City Hall.  And don't snicker. It actually is.  It's a Los Angeles City Hall wholly within the city limits.  Recognized by many, it will puzzle many more.  See Page 14, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: The building shown in the photo is commonly known as the Van Nuys City Hall.  But, because it houses various departments of the Los Angeles city government, its official title is Van Nuys Municipal Building.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY,NO.103 -- This woman (a tourist from Germany, who just happened along) is enjoying one of the most delightful little natural spots in town. You can bet it's not secluded Saturdays, Sundays! Answer, Page 36, Part l
Description.note: ANSWER: What else could it be but fascinating Fern Dell in Griffith Park where a winding walk through a foliage of ferns beside a murmuring stream helps one lose the nearby cry of the city?

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.108 -- Surely you dont have to get profane for you to realize what this is.  So what dam is it?  This is a racy place -- one kind of racing on one side and another on the other.  Isn't that enough. Turn to Page 18, Page lA.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the spillway of Hansen Dam.  (Didn't you notice those foothill peaks peeking through the opening?)  And sure, it's racy.  They have outboard motorboat races on the lake behind it and sports car races on a track directly below it.

Title: Know Your City No.109 Women and child walking the arcade of the San Fernando Mission, San Fernando, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.109, --Funny thing about this place--it's within Los Angeles city limits, but bears the name of another community.  Only one of its kind in the city limits.  Of course, it's heavy with history.  If you need it, see Page 30, Part2.
Description.note: ANSWER: What is pictured in the photo is, of course, a mission.  And the only mission within Los Angeles city limits is, despites its name, the San Fernando Mission, located on San Fernando Mission Road (surprise!) just east of Sepulveda Blvd.  Founded in 1797, it was the 17th in the California mission chain.

Title: Know Your City No.110 Church of the Blessed Sacrament Hollywood, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.110 -- This photo has so many clues as to its locality surely you can guess where it is. All that remains then, is what it is. All right, it's a church. But WHICH church? That is narrowing it down some. See Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: That enlarged photo of a movie actor and that high-perched globe at the Crossroads of the World and those palm trees should've told you that the photo was made on Sunset Blvd. The beautiful edifice itself is the church of the Blessed Sacrament at 6657 Sunset blvd., truly one of Hollywood's most magnificent churches.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY NO.111-- Honest, this photo wasn't made in Ireland, even if it does look like the County Cork.  Those who work here aren't interested in gross profits.  You know where it is, of course.  We're just being funny. (?)  See Page 28, Part II.
Description.note: ANSWER: It could, of course, be nothing else but Fishermen's Wharf (Berths 72-73) at Los Angeles Harbor, home of our great fleet of purse seiners.  The photo has caught the masts, the crow's nest, and the jumble of nets that symbolize this particular dock.  Oh, yes, the fishermen here aren't interested in gross profits.  They like net profits.  And that should take care of that.

Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the white, blue and golden temple of the Self-Realization Fellowship.  It is on Sunset Blvd. between Catalina and Edgemont Sts., just west of Vermont Ave.

Title: Know Your City No.116 Front view of Stimson House at 2421 S Figueroa Street Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.116 -- This is home to a lot of schoolteachers.  And it is passed by thousands upon thousands of people every day.  It is a famous old residence [sic].  Many probably have wondered about it.  Want to find out?  Page 38, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: A book could be written about his magnificent old place, which is located at 2421 S Figueroa St., near Adams Blvd. But, it be brief, it was built by the Stimsons, lumber tycoons; then was the home of the Maiers, the brewing family; next it was taken over by an SC fraternity, but the boys weren't the world's best neighbors, so Mrs. Estelle Doheny bought it and presented it to the Sisters of St. Joseph of Carondelet, who teach at the nearby St. Patrick, St. Brigid and Catholic Girls High Schools. (And who would never[sic] approve of such a long sentence.)|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #212 by the City of Los Angeles in 1979.

Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.119 E Building at the Hollenbeck Home for the Aged Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.119 -- All of the old-timers who know the city inside out and are such prolific letter writers will undoubtedly recognize this. Thousands of others, however will be stumped. It has history. But it's not a mission. See Page 37, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the E Building at the Hollenbeck Home for the Aged. Situated at 573 S Boyle Ave., the home is on a site that once was the residence of Mr. and Mrs. John E. Hollenbeck. That was in the 1860s. In 1895, more than 20 years before her death, the widowed Mrs. Hollenbeck founded and endowed the home. The building shown in the photo was built in 1918.

Name.architect: Kalionzes, Gus $q (William), $d 1910-1984|~|Walker, Albert R. $q (Albert Raymond), $d 1881-1958|~|Walker, Kalionzes & Klingerman, Architects|~|Klingerman, Charles A. $q (Arthur), $d 1912-1988

Title: Know Your City No.120 Entrance and faade of the Saint Sophia Greek Orthodox Cathedral, Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.120 -- A lot of movies helped to produce this impressive edifice.  And the people who go there are known to have a word for it.  But you don't need all these clues.  There are enough in the photo.  See Page 3, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yes, the Greeks have a word for it.  And the word for the Saint Sophia Greek Orthodox Cathedral is-- magnificent.  It is at 1324 S Normandie Ave. and was built and presented to the local Greek community by the late film executive, Charles P. Skouras|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #123 by the City of Los Angeles in 1973.|~|St. Sophia Cathedral, located at 1324 South Normandy Ave., opened in 1952. It was commissioned by theater executive Charles R. Skouras. Designed by the firm Walker, Kalionzes & Klingerman, it is frequently attributed to Gus Kalionzes. Artist William Chavalas, who trained at the Academy of arts in Athens and was the artistic director at 20th Century Fox designing film sets and movie theaters, created the wall paintings and designed the stained glass. St. Sophia is Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monument #120.

Title: Know Your City No.121 Los Angeles' steepest hill the 2100 block of W. Fargo St., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.121 -- Aha!  This is the time we've got you.  This place has a certain distinction naturally.  Otherwise, we would not have taken a picture of it.  Okay, so where is it and what is its distinction?  You'll be enlightened on Page 11, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is what is officially recorded as Los Angeles' steepest hill -- the 2100 block of W Fargo St.  It has a 32% grade and dips down from its lofty height to meet Allesandro St., where that thoroughfare intersects with Glendale Blvd.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.124 -- Now you know very well this isnt some old abandoned pier.  It's old and abandoned, all right.  But no pier.  A Familiar sight on a busy street, many will know what it is.  But do you?  If not, see Page 36, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the southern end of the old Pacific Electric trestle over Fletcher Drive, just west of Riverside Drive.  Over this high bridge, before they were replaced by busses, used to roll the interurban cars to Glendale and Burbank.

Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the entrance to one of the city's larger hospitals, Cedars of Lebanon, at 4833 Fountain Ave., out Hollywood way.  What are Cedrus libani? Cedars of Lebanon, naturally.|~|Cedars of Lebanon and Mount Sinai Hospitals merged in 1961 to form Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.

Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is a corner of the rapidly rising steel framework for the new County Courthouse at 1st and Hill Sts. And for which a portion of Bunker Hill was torn away.  This was too easy.  Because surely you spotted the Law Building and the Hall of Records in the background.|~|In 2002 the Los Angeles County Central Courthouse was renamed Stanley Mosk Courthouse in memory of Supreme Court Justice Stanley Mosk.

Description.note: ANSWER: The figure in the statue with his walking staff and arm around an Indian boy is, of course, Father Junipero Serra.  This rustically mounted sculpture besides an equally rustic fountain and pool stands in Brand Park and, in the background just across the street, is the San Fernando Mission.

Title: Know Your City No.128 Veterans Neuropsychiatric Hospital in Sepulveda, San Fernando Valley, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.128 -- This one is going to puzzle a lot of people.  It isn't a fortress.  It isn't UCLA.  It isn't even Disneyland.  And now that you know what it isn't, you may use your best judgment as to what it IS.  It's a pretty fair bet you'll miss it.  Just to check up see the answer on Page 12, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: The blocklike buildings in the photo constitute the main cluster at the Veterans Neuropsychiatric Hospital at Sepulveda. Here, war-weary minds are treated; and incidentally, functions of the hospital were detailed in a recent feature series in The Times.  The hospital is located in the San Fernando Valley on Lassen St., just west of Sepulveda Blvd.

Description.note: ANSWER: Sure, what else could it be but the Sepulveda Blvd. tunnel beneath the extended runways of the Los Angeles International Airport?  Too easy.

Title: Know Your City No.130 View of hills and part of the Owens Valley aqueduct called the Cascades
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.130 -- This is a river that is a long way from home.  And it has been splashing down this spectacular spillway since 1913.  There's nothing like it in the city.  Yes, it's in the city.  See answer on Page 36, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the Cascades, which tumbles beneath Foothill Blvd. and the Golden State Freeway out beyond San Fernando.  This is Owens River water, pictured at the terminus of the 233-mile Owens River Aqueduct.  It is, of course, a project of the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power and some of that water cascading down there could very well have provided your morning shower.

Title: Know Your City No.131 Entrance and tower of Los Angeles' Wrigley Field on E 42nd Place at Avalon Blvd
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.131 -- Just because a lot of hits have been made here, you might think it is a movie studio.  But it isn't, by gum.  And even if cherubs do cavort here, it isn't heaven, either.  No labor trouble, but plenty of strikes.  See Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: With all those corny clues, you surely were able to guess that the structure shown in the photo is Wrigley Field on E 42nd Place at Avalon Blvd., home of the Los Angeles Angels baseball club.|~|Los Angeles' Wrigley Field was built by William Wrigley Jr. in the 1920s.  The structure was demolished in 1966.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 132 -- Here's one that will stump you.  This unique, castle-like structure is on a prominent thoroughfare.  Once a private residence, it has an interior which matches the exterior for unusual medieval design.  Turn to Page 38, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: This fine old former residence, located at 3330 W Adams Blvd., now serves as headquarters for the Church Federation of Los Angeles.  And, if you guessed this one, you really know you city.|~|The house was built for Los Angeles department store merchant John J. Haggarty.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.133 -- Just because it supervises a lot of take-offs and oversees several strips doesnt mean that this is headquarters for a bunch of burlesque queens.  With those clues and the photo hints it should be easy.  If not, see Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: To be perfectly plane about it, the structure in the photo could be nothing else but the control tower at Los Angeles International Airport.  And if you didn't recognize it, you're just not on the beam.

Name.subject: Los Angeles Owens River Aqueduct System
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.135 One of the Van Norman Lakes, Owens River Aqueduct reservoir, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.135 -- Los Angeles residents should recognize this.  It is pretty important to their existence.  Its name was changed not too long ago and it became a lake.  But its function is more vital than boating.  See Page 20, Part lA.
Description.note: ANSWER: The body of water shown in the photo is one of the Van Norman Lakes.  Known until recently as the Upper San Fernando Reservoir, it is used by the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power as the main storage place for the precious water from the Owens River, arriving here via a 233-mile aqueduct.  It is adjacent to Sepulveda Blvd. in the northwest corner of the San Fernando Valley.  It and a similar nearby reservoir were renamed in honor of late H.A. Van Norman, once general manager of the Department of Water and Power, who played a leading role in construction of the Owens River Aqueduct.

Title: Know Your City No.137 Sepulveda Dam and a portion of the Sepulveda Flood Control Basin, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 137 -- There are quite a lot of things this isn't: It isn't a race track, it isn't a polo field, and it isn't a stadium.  Matter of fact there is only one thing it IS.  And, if you can guess, you're good.  See answer, Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: What the photo shows is Sepulveda Dam and a portion of the huge Sepulveda Flood Control Basin.  It is situated just west of Sepulveda blvd. and extends between Magnolia and Victory Blvds. In the general vicinity of Van Nuys.

Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 138 -- These stately columns comprise a corner of a former residence that now is headquarters for a Community Chest agency.  You can't see it, but there's a building in back where babies come and go.  See Page 29, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: It probably wasn't fair to show such a small portion of the place, but this is the Children's Home Society of California, a licensed adoption agency at 3100 W Adams Blvd.  But, the portion that was pictured should have been readily recognized because it faces the busy intersection of W Adams Blvd. and Arlington Ave.|~|CHS was founded in the 1890s by Dr. and Mrs. J. R. Townsend to assist homeless and abandoned children.

Title: Know Your City No.140 Eastern end of Hyperion Ave. Bridge and Victory Memorial, Atwater Village (Los Angeles), 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.140 -- These things keep getting easier and easier.  Surely you recognize this scene.  It isn't a Answer, even if it does have the same name.  See?  Even if it is easy, we keep giving it away.  What is it?  See Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: It's the Hyperion Ave. Bridge that swoops down over Riverside Drive and the section of it shown in the photo is near its eastern end where it intersects with Glendale Blvd. out in the Atwater district.  Sewer?  Well, we have a Hyperion sewer, don't' we?  Admittedly pretty far-fetched, but then...|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #164 by the City of Los Angeles in 1976.

Title: Know Your City No.141 Entrance and faade of old Bimini Hot Springs and Bath Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.141 -- Lots of people used to get all steamed up in this place.  Long closed, it once was world famous and one of the top tourist attractions.  It wasn't a billiard parlor, but there was plenty of pool.  See the answer on Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the entrance to the old Bimini Hot Springs and Bath.  Situated at 180 Bimini Place, just east of Vermont Ave., "Bimini" enjoyed years of great popularity as a health spot-- had mineral baths, steam baths and no less than three swimming pools.|~|Bimini Baths feed by hot mineral springs, 2,000 feet underground was founded by Dr. David W. Edwards in 1902.   The baths closed in the 1950s.  In the 1990s Los Angeles Eco-Village bought the buildings and grounds.

Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the old abandoned Pacific Electric tunnel through which interurban cars used to rumble from Glendale Blvd. to the Subway Terminal.

Title: Know Your City No.147 View from underneath of viaduct and streets at 1st Street and Beverly Blvd. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.147 -- If you can read the numbers on that bus, you've got it made.  It is just possible that viaduct and all those converging streets may confuse you a bit and you won't know what it is.  Answer on Page 30, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: You really should have recognized the scene in the photo because it shows the viaduct where 1st St. becomes Beverly Blvd. and, what's more, shows 2nd St. where IT becomes Glendale Blvd. and, all in all, it's pretty doggone complicated.

Title: Know Your City No.147 Shakespeare Bridge and surrounding homes on Franklin Ave. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.148 -- Now here's one that is going to throw a lot of people.  Of course, it's a bridge.  But what bridge?  And where? Even with the fancy cupolas, it really isn't a very important bridge.  Except to people who cross it.  See Page 7, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This is the nice little bridge that carries Franklin Ave. in 3800 block out Los Feliz way.  What it carries Franklin Ave. over is not much more than a weedy little gulch.  But it's handy.|~|Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #126 by the City of Los Angeles in 1974.

Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.150 Front of main building of John Marshall High School in the Los Feliz-Silver Lake district, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.150 -- Well, the young people who occupy this building call themselves Barristers.  They aren't lawyers, but the institution is named after one.  And that should suffice in the hint department.  See Page 37, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: The handsome structure in the photo is the main building of John Marshall High School at 3939 Tracy St., in the Los Feliz-Silver Lake district.  Inasmuch as the school is named after the great Chief Justice it is only natural that its athletic teams are known as the Barristers.

Title: Know Your City No.151 Los Angeles River looking north beneath the 7th St. Bridge toward the 6th St. Bridge.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.151 -- Oh, this is silly.  Of course, it's a river.  And it's foolish to ask which one.  Because how many rivers does Los Angeles have?  So let's just leave it that you're to guess WHERE along the river this is.  Page 19, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Yep, it's the Los Angeles River, all right--Looking north beneath the 7th St. Bridge toward the 6th St. Bridge.  That shiny stuff in the picture, incidentally, is water.

Title: Know Your City No.154 Angled view of front of Ebell Club, at 4400 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO. 154 -- This is the front of one of the city's foremost centers of culture and education.  Just behind camera is busiest street in town.  In its present location since 1927, it has theater in back.  See Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Although only a small portion of it was shown you should've recognized the Ebell Club, which is at 4400 Wilshire Blvd., corner of Lucerne Blvd.  And we made it easy by mentioning the theater, the Wilshire Ebell Theater, which is at the rear of the premises.|~|The Ebell of Los Angeles is an educational and philanthropic organization founded by women in 1894.  The mission is to participate in and encourage the educational, cultural and social growth of the diverse Los Angeles community.  In honor of Dr.Adrian Ebell.  --From Ebell of Los Angeles mission statement.  Declared Historic-Cultural Monument #250 by the City of Los Angeles in 1982.

Title: Know Your City No.155 Entrance to Los Angeles' first private community, Fremont Place at Wilshire Blvd.-Rossmore Ave.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.155 -- Through these portals pass some of the city's top citizens.  Inside posts, very private.  Outside, very public.  Answer Page 8, Part2.
Description.note: ANSWER: The imposing pillars in the pictures is the entrance from Wilshire Blvd. (at the intersection of Rossmore Ave.) to Fremont Place, one of the city's most exclusive residential districts.

Title: Know Your City No.157 St. Angelo Hotel at 237 N Grand Ave. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.157 -- Take a good look, because this old landmark, since 1887, won't be around much longer.  Thousands pass it daily.  Many will recognize it, but they'll be darned if they remember where it is.  See Page 6, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the old St. Angelo Hotel at 237 N Grand Ave., just off Temple St. Now , do you remember?  Anyway, it was recently ordered vacated by the Board of Health and soon will be torn down.  And so another famous old landmark will live only in the photo files.

Title: Know Your City No.167 Exterior of Mirror Building at 2nd and Spring Streets with rolls of newsprint in foreground Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.167 -- It borders on ridiculous to imagine that there's anyone in town who won't recognize this building.  But, just in case, the photographer picked a foreground that makes it a dead giveaway.  Not much point in turning to Page 32, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The modern structure in the photo could be northing else, of course, but the Mirror Building at 2nd and Spring Sts. And, while artistically symbolic, those rolls of newsprint in the foreground eliminated any possible guesswork.

Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988

Title: Know Your City No.171 Murals at the entrance of Los Angeles County General Hospital
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.171 -- Although thousands of people pass beneath these colorful and impressive murals, chances are that few will know where they are.  Hint: this ceiling has something to do with healing.  A well-known figure is seen at top center, right.  To learn the correct answer, turn to Page 30, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: The tridomed murals are in the portlier of the main entrance to the General Hospital.  And there may be those who recognized the portrait in right upper center (the one being held by the young child) as that of Hippocrates, the Greek physician so revered by the medical profession.|~|The murals were created in 1932.

Title: Know Your City No.172 Los Angeles City Jail building and surrounding grounds in 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.172 -- This isnt a watch factory, although a lot of time made here.  And the Communists wish they had so many cells.  Even if this is seldom-seen angle, you surely can guess after those hints.  See Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Just to let down the bars and tell you, the building in the photo is the City Jail.  The picture was taken from Elysian Park Drive on the west side of the Los Angeles River.

Title: Know Your City No.173 Southbound lanes of Pasadena Freeway going through Elysian Park, Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.173 -- Told you yesterday you wouldn't get any clues with today's photo.  Heavens, you shouldn't need them because everyone certainly must recognize this scene.  If you really must know, turn to Page 33, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Naturally, it is the Pasadena Freeway as it zips through Elysian Park.  Photo was made from the Park Row Drive overpass, looking south high above the inbound lanes.  Obvious postscript: It was NOT made during the rush hour.

Title: Know Your City No.181 Empty beach and walkway at Venice Beach, Calif. looking south toward Playa del Rey
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.181 -- No, this isn't the edge of the Sahara, despite all the sand, palm tress and those oil wells in the distance.  It's within the city limits, which contain few stretches of sand like this.  For the answer, see Page 32, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Now that you think of it, the beach shown in the photo is the broad expanse of the municipal beach at Venice, looking south toward Playa del Rey.  That horizontal black line in center of the picture is the Pacific Ocean.  What the photo lacks: Bathing beauties.

Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.182 Statues of saber-tooth tigers at La Brea Tar Pits Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.182 -- Hold that tiiiger!  Determined to beat the tar out of each other, these two animals are putting the bite on each other in a historic spot that is near a busy boulevard.  If that isn't enough, see Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This statue of a couple of unfriendly saber-tooth tigers is in the famous La Brea Pits in Hancock Park on Wilshire Blvd.  That pool of smooth black stuff behind them is one of the eeringly bubbling pits of fossil-bearing asphalt deposits of the Pleistocene Epoch. (Got all that from a card tacked up on the fence.)|~|The sculpture was created by Hermann T. Beck, based on drawings by Joseph L. Roop.

Title: Know Your City No.185 Corner of the Life Science Building and construction at UCLA in 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.185 -- All you need to solve this one is a little deduction.  Obviously, it's a school -- and a new building.  Now: What school has been doing a lot of building?  What school?  What building?  See Page 30, Part 2.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is an interesting stairway and one corner of the new and modern Life Science Building at UCLA.

Title: Know Your City No.186; Bridge over Grand Canal with oil wells in background at Venice, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.186 -- Just because these artists are painting on the Grand Canal, don't get the idea they are in Italy.  It's a canal all right, and others are nearby.  Answer on Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This is the Grand Canal of Venice--Venice, Cal.  Photograph of this section of the beach city's long-abandoned--and now revived--idea to emulate Venice, Italy, with a system of canals, was made looking south of the N Venice Blvd. bridge over the Grand Canal.

Title: Know Your City No.189 Cummings Block building on the northwest corner of E 1st St. and Boyle Ave Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.189 -- First, you should have a confession: Couldn't learn too much about this old building ourselves.  But, it is on a prominent corner on the East Side and has been there since 1889.  Swanky then.  Answer on Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The cupolaed structure in the photo is, if you couldn't read the sign, the old Cummings Block on the northwest corner of E 1st St. and Boyle Ave.  It was built originally as a hotel and it still is one.

Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.195 Entrance to Times Boys Club at 2635 Pasadena Ave. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.195 -- This is a much publicized place (or we'll know the reason why.) But, we'll bet there are few who will recognize it, by gym-iny.  Benefits from a football game.  Surely, you can guess now.  Answer on Page 30, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is the main entrance and a portion of the Times Boys Club at 2635 Pasadena Ave.  As we said, many appreciate it, but few-other than the lucky kids who belong to it- would receives most of the benefits from the traditional Los Angeles Rams vs. Washington Redskins professional football game every August.

Subject: Fire fighters--Monuments--California--Los Angeles|~|Landmarks
Name.subject: Los Angeles (Calif.). Fire Dept.
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.197 Memorial for firemen of the Los Angeles Fire Department
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.197 -- Of course, you will recognize this as a memorial.  But, what and where is it?  Hint: Although the trees obscure any definite clues, it is in a very prominent spot of the city. If you can't guess, take a peek at Page 28, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: The monument was erected in memoriam "to the fighting men of the Fire Department, city of Los Angeles, who met violent death while in performance of their duties."  It stands in the little park on the south side of the City Hall, near the intersection of 1st and Spring Sts., and was dedicated Oct. 14, 1944.

Name.subject: Terminal Annex Post Office (Los Angeles, Calif.)
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.198; Cityscape view looking north from the City Hall tower Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.198 -- How lazy can you get? Sure, this is a bird's-eye view of the city.  Sure, it was shot from the City Hall tower.  All you have to figure out is which way camera was pointing.  Easy? Some will miss.  See Page 20, Part 1A.
Description.note: ANSWER: There were a million landmarks to tell you that the camera was pointed north from the City Hall tower.  In the foreground are the top of the Federal Building and the Hollywood-Santa Ana Freeway.  Off to the right are the clump of trees that is the Plaza and beyond it the Post Office Terminal Annex.  At the extreme left N Broadway heads toward the tree-covered hills of Elysian Park.

Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.199; Cityscape view looking east from the City Hall tower in Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.199 -- Here's the second of four directional views of the city taken from the City Hall tower.  And, like all of them, you should have no trouble figuring out which way the camera pointed.  Too easy?  See Page 36, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: East.  That's the view from the City Hall tower.  In the foreground the top of the new Police Administration Building.  At lower right the intersection of 1st and San Pedro Sts.  Slanting across the photo just above center the Los Angeles River.  Three bridges are visible--1st St., 4th St. and 6th St.

Subject: Radio--Antennas|~|Landmarks|~|Environment
Name.subject: Los Angeles Times Building (Los Angeles, Calif.)
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.200; Cityscape view looking south by west from the City Hall tower in Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.200 -- Well, here we are at the 200 mark in this [series].  And, without trying to be cute about it, this picture taken from the City Hall tower is, if nothing else, symbolic of the whole idea.  Of course, you know direction camera is facing.  Don't fret, series is going to continue.  See Page 34, Part [?].
Description.note: ANSWER: The photo, looking south by west from the City Hall tower, is a panorama of the downtown business district.  And, of course, it wasn't expected to baffle anybody.  Too many prominent landmarks, including the Times and Mirror Buildings in center foreground.

Subject: Automobile parking--California--Los Angeles|~|Express highways--California--Los Angeles County|~|Landmarks|~|Environment
Name.subject: Stanley Mosk Courthouse (Los Angeles, Calif.)--Design and construction
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.201; Cityscape view looking west from the City Hall tower in Los Angeles, Calif., 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.201 -- Maybe this view from City Hall tower wasn't such a hot idea after all.  Too easy.  This one should be, if only because the other three already have been published.  That leaves you one choice.  See Page 35, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: West. That's the way you were looking in the photo from the City Hall tower.  That's the roof of the Hall of Records in the foreground.  Over at the left is the Law Building and steel structure for the new County Courthouse.  Beyond Temple St. at the right it the four-level interchange of the freeways and, way at the left, Beverly Blvd. goes over Belmont Hill.  Hollywood and the Hollywood Hills are out there in the haze somewhere.

Title: Know Your City No.203 Private residence, Castle of Enchantment at 4857 Melrose Ave. Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.203 -- Nope, this isn't part of Disneyland.  And it isnt in jolly old England, either.  It is right here in Los Angeles and fronts on one of our busier thoroughfare.  A unique residence.  Find the answer on Page 29, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: This "Castle of Enchantment," as the tablet in the entrance arch identifies it, is the unusual home, created by themselves, of Milton and Josie Hopkins.  It is at 4857 Melrose Ave., just east of Western Ave.

Name.subject: Glendale High School (Glendale, Calif.)
Rights.rightsHolderContact: UCLA Charles E. Young Research Library Department of Special Collections, A1713 Young Research Library, Box 951575, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1575. E-mail: spec-coll@library.ucla.edu. Phone: (310)825-4988
Relation.isPartOf: Los Angeles Times Photographic Archive. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Title: Know Your City No.206 Grounds and buildings of Glendale Union High School, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.206 -- Here's another gem from the Jewel City.  They may have a lot of class but the young people around this place are known as Dynamiters.  (Which should be con-fusing.) But don't blow up.  The answer's on Page 33, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: Dynamiters?  Jewel City? Sure, what else could it be but a section of the handsome Glendale Union High School?  Shucks, anybody'd a-knowed that.

Title: Know Your City No.209 View of the Eagle Rock boulder Los Angeles, Calif.
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.209 -- This is strictly for the bird.  Nevertheless, there is a community, all within Los Angeles city limits, named after this big boulder.  We're getting tired of giving clues that make this so easy.  See Page 32, Part ll.
Description.note: ANSWER: This is going to be brief because the subject of the photo was so obvious: Sure, it is the Eagle Rock in the Annandale Hills and after which the community farthermost in the northeastern section of Los Angeles' city limits is located.  Dumb remark: It's been there for years.

Title: Know Your City No.221 View over fence of buildings of Ramona Convent in Alhambra, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.221 -- Standing high on a hill and dominating surrounding countryside is this famous institution.  It is a familiar sight to Southlanders.  But many may not know of its interesting history.  Answer on Page 30, Part l.
Description.note: ANSWER: Shown in the photo is a portion-including its three imposing towers-of the Ramona Convent in Alhambra.  Opened by the Sisters of the Holy Names in 1889, it is the Southland's oldest Catholic school for girls.  This hill upon which it stands and some surrounding property was presented to the Sisters by the Shorb family, which,  at one time, owned most of what is now Alhambra and San Marino.  And the convent is named after one of the Shorb daughters, Ramona, and not, as many presume, after the Spanish girl who became Alessandro's bride.

Beautiful spot with a strange calmness and where, in a shrine just behind the impressive portal in the photo, is a portion of the ashes of Mahatma Gandhi.|~|Golden Lotus Archway.

Title: Know Your City No.249 Front porch and marker of Avila Adobe on Olvera Street, Los Angeles, 1956
Description.caption: KNOW YOUR CITY, NO.249 -- How better to begin the windup of this series than at the beginning.  And that's what you see here--the beginning.  It is probably one of city's most historical structures.  If you don't know the answer, then look on Page 14, Part 1.
Description.note: ANSWER: The structure in the photo is the Avila Adobe, generally conceded to be the oldest building in Los Angeles.  It is located at 14 Olvera Street.  Built in 1818 by Don Francisco Avila, it served as American headquarters in 1847 when U.S. troops captured the city.  It has the further distinction of having flown four flags--Spanish, Mexican, the California Republic, and the Stars and Stripes.  And, as Consuela de Bonzo, "Queen" of Olvera Street, puts it: "It is the only place in the world around here like that."

Title: Attorney A. L. Wirin with Rena Frye and her sons, Ronald and Marquette at Los Angeles courthouse, 1965
Description.caption: FIGURES IN RIOT CASE-Attorney A. L. Wirin, left, with Mrs. Rena Frye, accused of interfering with officers who arrested her sons, Ronald, center, and Marquette, right. Incident touched off riot.
Description.note: The incident that is credited to starting the 1965 Watts Riot involved Marquette and Ronald Frye who on August 11, 1965 were stopped by a police officer for erratic driving. While being questioned their mother, Rena arrived. At some point an altercation between the police and the three family members ensued which led to the arrest of all three. A crowd that had gathered and were angered by the treatment of the family began throwing bottles at the police.

Title: Minh Son Nguyen playing baseball with therapist Edith Gillespie at Orthopaedic Hospital in Los Angeles, Calif., 1966
Description.caption: PART OF THE THERAPY-Minh Son Nguyen, 11, Vietnamese war victim who lost left hand when he was 3, swings baseball bat with help of new artificial hand at Orthopaedic Hospital. Catching for him is Miss Edith Gillespie, occupational therapist, who said that swinging bat is first stage of Minh's therapy. He'll learn to use the hand in other tasks in next few weeks. Boy and sister, 9, were adopted last July by Phillip Rockstroth family, Northridge, whose son, Dennis, met them in a Vietnam orphanage.

The start on Figueroa Boulevard appeared to ba scene of mass confusion with three runners breaking across the starting line while other entrants were waving to friends or checking their watches. Title: Arnel Salvatierra and his attorney, Marcia Morrisey at his arraignment in Glendale, Calif., 1986
Description.caption: Arraigned--Arnel Salvatierra and his attorney, Marcia Morrisey, as he pleaded not guilty Thursday in Glendale Municipal Court to the slaying of this father, Filipino-American newspaper executive Oscar Salvatierra, 41. His 17-year-old son, who will be tried as an adult in the Feb. 19 killing, and his girlfriend, Teressa Deburger, who has been charged as an accomplice, face a preliminary hearing May 30 in Glendale. The death of the father was at first thought related to political turmoil in the Philippines.

Title: Police victims and their lawyer and family at the LA Press Club, 1967.
Description.caption: PROTESTERS - Interviewed by newsmen were these protesters of police action in breaking up peace marchers during the President's visit. From left, Steven Sokol, who charged he was a victim of police brutality; Philip Chronis, attorney, American Civil Liberties Union member; George Slaff, head of Southern California ACLU; Dr. mortimer Roth, a dentist, with son marc, 11, standing, both listed as victims, and Aris Agnagnos, a member of the board of directors of the ACLU.  Meanwhile, a city councilman demanded a full-scale investigation.
Description.note: Image accompanied by caption is 236643-19-1.|~|The allegations of brutality stem from Pres. Johnson's visit to Century Plaza and the attendant demonstration.

Description.caption: MOURNERS, ALL - Part of the throng outside Alhambra funeral chapel as services were conducted yesterday for little Kathy.  For hours preceding the sorrowful services hundreds of persons silently passed by her casket to view her.  She lay in death holding her favorite doll.
Description.note: Kathy Fiscus died after falling into a San Marino well. Rescue workers were not able to reach her in time.

Title: Hugh Hefner (left), Mayor Tom Bradley (center) and Los Angeles Times Publisher Otis Chandler at reception for Freedom of Press exhibit, Los Angeles, 1980
Description.caption: A LOOK AT FREEDOM  Mayor Bradley, Times Publisher Otis Chandler and Hugh Hefner of Playboy view documents at reception for the Freedom of Press exhibit on the fifth floor of the Times Building.  The exhibit will be open to the public Tuesday through March 14.  It includes 15 historical papers, four from the trial of John Peter Zenger.  The collection was borrowed from the Chicago Public Library by the Playboy Foundation, sponsor of the exhibit.
Description.note: Image that accompanies caption in print is b1134_291594-17a.  Image has not been scanned as of November 12, 2008.

Title: Diane Carol Harris is treated for broken arm at Van Nuys Receiving Hospital after surviving plane crash, 1949.
Description.caption: LOSES FATHER  Diane Carol Harris, 5 , of 7260 Bellaire Ave.,  North Hollywood, is treated for broken arm at Van Nuys Receiving Hospital.  Father, Harley S. Harris, was killed, while mother was among injured.
Description.note: Father, Harley S. Harris, was killed, while mother was among injured after a Standard Airlines C-46 crashed in the Santa Susanna Mountains near Simi Valley and Chatsworth.

Title: Wreckage of Standard Airlines C-46 crash, 1949.
Description.caption: MANGLED  Battered fuselage and wing section of the air liner.  The plane was a C-46 Standard Airlines transport, a former twin-engine Commando.  It was flying at about 1600 feet a mile and a half northeast of Chatsworth Reservoir when it crashed.
Description.note: Plane crashed in the Santa Susana Mountains near Simi Valley and Chatsworth.

Description.caption: DEATH SCENE  Contents of ill-fated transport are flung in wild disarray.  Tail section rises bleakly above scene.
Description.note: The plane crashed in the Santa Susana Mountains near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Passenger cabin of crashed Standard Airlines C-46, 1949.
Description.caption: CLOSE-UP  Wreckage of Standard Airlines C-46 lies on side of steep canyon in Santa Susana Mountains, surrounded by dead and injured, as rescue work begins.  Picture shows how whole section of passenger cabin was sheared away, hurling burned and mangled bodies among boulders 30 yards away.  Another plane reported tragedy.
Description.note: The plane crashed in the Santa Susana mountains, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Rescue workers and survivors stand looking at the wreckage of Standard Airlines C-46, 1949.
Description.caption: BODIES SCATTERED  The dead, dying and injured were flung through the inferno like dolls when Standard Airlines plane crashed in Santa Susana Mountains.  First rescuers from the Simi area raced among the screaming victims, passing by the dead in frantic efforts to save living.  Girls body was found under wing.
Description.note: Plane crashed in Santa Susana Mountains near Simi Valley and Chatsworth.

Description.note: The plane, a Standard Airlines C-46, crashed in the Santa Susana Mountains near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Description.note: Plane crashed in Santa Susana Mountains near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Investigator probably at the home of murder victim Mabel Monahan, Burbank, 1953
